<TITLE> Emergency will hike commodity prices further: Akbar Ali </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 9 (bdnews24.com) - Regulatory Reforms Commission chairman Akbar Ali Khan Saturday demanded an immediate withdrawal of what he called a state of emergency in political and economic arenas. Speaking at a roundtable on "Future of democracy in Bangladesh", he said: "At present the state of emergency in prevailing in two areas, one is politics, and the other is the economy. The price of essentials has crossed all limits of tolerance. If the state of emergency becomes permanent, the problem will aggravate." The roundtable was organised at the National Press Club VIP Lounge on the first anniversary of the publication of Dainik Manavjamin's weekly issue. Khan said: "Although there are drawbacks in democracy, there is no better system than democracy." He also opined that a constitutionally fragile situation was now prevailing. Gano Forum president Dr Kamal Hossain demanded a fair election and said: "The government will have to hold a fair election so that none can snatch our achievements." He also urged the government to hold dialogue with the representatives of all strata of people. Awami League presidium member Amir Hossain Amu said: "The Awami League wants a sustainable democracy. We are making a coordinated proposal through talks with like-minded parties." He said if the voter list was amended in the past following the guidance of the High Court, the present crisis would not arise. Amu said the Awami League wanted a fair and acceptable election. Senior lawyer barrister Rafique-ul Huq said, "There will be no election with the state of emergency in force. For establishing democracy, the independence of the judiciary has to be ensured. Fair election is the only way to establishing democracy." Former secretary Asafuddowla presented the keynote paper. Top political leaders and professionals participated in the discussion, speaking in favour of the immediate withdrawal of the state of emergency. bdnews24.
